00:06:18.600 --> 00:06:24.119
byproduct of COVID, which was, has been incredibly disruptive personally, professionally, sort of

00:06:24.119 --> 00:06:32.279
across the board. We were not able in 2020 to host any guests at Wrigley Field. We ended up

00:06:32.279 --> 00:06:38.279
being able to play a shortened season, but we took that downtime as an organization to ask some tough

00:06:38.279 --> 00:06:43.959
questions on what do we want the business to look like in three to five years? Because we kind of

00:06:44.119 --> 00:06:51.959
had this extra window of time in which we could plan and prepare. And so from a game day presentation

00:06:51.959 --> 00:06:59.000
and experience standpoint, what that turned into, we completely overhauled the access control process.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:04.679
So historically we'd have these long lines and you'd have to go through this metal detector and

00:07:04.679 --> 00:07:10.440
it was just, you'd have someone like poking in your bag. It was not a very welcoming experience

00:07:10.440 --> 00:07:18.200
and so through some new technology and changes that we deployed in our security footprint,

00:07:18.200 --> 00:07:26.920
we're able to completely overhaul that entire process. And once you get into venue,

00:07:26.920 --> 00:07:35.399
we put forward, we moved cash from our venue and put a big emphasis on contactless ordering for food and beverage.

00:07:35.559 --> 00:07:41.160
Data science specifically played into that in several components because it's thinking about

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:47.559
balancing the guest experience. There's certainly some financial components, some trade-offs that

00:07:47.559 --> 00:07:55.799
we had to evaluate in terms of staffing and what we could actually deliver to our guests.

00:07:55.799 --> 00:08:03.399
But it was sort of data, it was a very data driven process. We were able to do a lot of

00:08:03.559 --> 00:08:11.160
it was a very data forward sort of process and understanding the various stakeholders

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:13.799
and what's important to each group and sort of how do we find the right balance.

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:20.519
Definitely. And Chris, I didn't see your question in the chat when I brought up Moneyball before.

00:08:21.239 --> 00:08:23.640
So do you want to introduce yourself and ask that question?

00:08:25.559 --> 00:08:32.200
Sure, why not? So Chase, I'm a data scientist here at Air Force Special Operations Command

00:08:32.840 --> 00:08:36.760
and the question that I had posted on there is just how much influence did

00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:45.159
Movie Moneyball have on your job? Yeah, the short answer is a lot.

00:08:47.719 --> 00:08:49.400
Sorry, were you going to say something else, Chris?

00:08:51.640 --> 00:08:58.760
No, I'm good. Okay, the short answer is a lot. I was fortunate enough to play baseball

