really understanding the Moneyball type metrics that we can produce. On the other end of the

00:10:33.479 --> 00:10:40.520
spectrum, you get folks who they sort of live and breathe it. And you've seen a huge emphasis from

00:10:40.760 --> 00:10:46.039
I think you've seen a huge emphasis from all the major front offices in trying to find ways to

00:10:46.679 --> 00:10:51.400
interject more analytics into their decision making, into their player development,

00:10:52.359 --> 00:10:58.599
and ultimately trying to position each player for success. I think how that actually manifests

00:10:58.599 --> 00:11:08.039
on an individual player level varies quite a bit. Thank you. Jeff, I see you just put a

00:11:08.039 --> 00:11:15.640
question in the chat as well. Would you want to ask that one live? Or I can read it.

00:11:17.880 --> 00:11:25.080
Yep. Sorry, I'm on baby duty right now. Hey, Chase, long time.

00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:32.599
Yeah, good to see you too. I'm curious what the tech stack looks like

00:11:33.479 --> 00:11:40.440
at the Cubs. And is it different between, I don't know the terminology you're using,

00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:44.599
but like retail and professional, like the folks that are doing the actual Moneyball stuff,

00:11:44.599 --> 00:11:49.799
are they using a different tech stack? And yeah, how is that different from what we were doing

00:11:50.840 --> 00:11:56.599
seven, eight years ago? Yeah, it's a good question and awesome to see a friendly face.

00:11:57.400 --> 00:12:03.799
Yeah, for context, Jeff and I worked together for five or six years, and then we've both gone on

00:12:04.919 --> 00:12:12.119
our separate ways. So briefly, so our tech stack on the business side, I think relatively standard.

00:12:12.119 --> 00:12:16.919
We have a fairly robust data warehouse infrastructure. Currently, we're sitting

00:12:16.919 --> 00:12:25.239
on an Oracle tech stack and we have our IT team formally owns data ingestion, all the ETL work.

00:12:25.239 --> 00:12:31.239
They also own our business intelligence layer. So a lot of the ways I sit on top of that

00:12:32.039 --> 00:12:38.599
in my day-to-day, I have our, more specifically, our studio open pretty much every single day,

00:12:40.520 --> 00:12:47.799
run most of my sort of analytical work through our... On the baseball operation side, to be honest,

00:12:47.799 --> 00:12:54.440
we're almost two completely separate companies. I know they have a very heavy R and Python

00:12:54.440 --> 00:13:01.320
base. They also do a lot of internal custom app development work. And so there's more of a

