coming out of R or Python and then embedding those into applications that they can push out

00:13:12.919 --> 00:13:22.679
to coaches and players. Thanks, Jeff, for your question. And I did just want to say,

00:13:22.679 --> 00:13:27.640
if anybody writes a question and you don't want me to have you read it out loud, or if you're in

00:13:27.640 --> 00:13:32.760
a loud cafe or something, you could put a little star at the end and then I'll know to just read it

00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:38.599
too. But Ronald, I saw that you had also asked a question in the chat earlier.

00:13:40.119 --> 00:13:42.679
Can I give you the mic and have you add some context there too?

00:13:43.479 --> 00:13:50.359
Yeah, sure. I always like to hear myself talk. I am not a data analyst. I just sort of play

00:13:51.239 --> 00:14:01.559
a role in the data analysis for the AI network. My question has to do with how are your projects

00:14:02.440 --> 00:14:10.039
or areas of analysis determined? And I ask that because I find myself, at least in this business,

00:14:11.320 --> 00:14:17.080
working a little bit with ad hoc where I have to keep an eye on a lot of what is going on in

00:14:17.479 --> 00:14:27.719
fiscal or operations or patient throughput or whatnot. And I do get a certain amount of

00:14:28.840 --> 00:14:34.280
guidance from, oh, we have this problem, solve it. But yet it's people who really have no idea

00:14:34.280 --> 00:14:43.960
how to go about that. So actually doing a very in-depth scope of work analysis becomes critical.

00:14:44.679 --> 00:14:48.280
And I'm wondering what sort of a situation you've encountered there.

00:14:49.559 --> 00:14:53.719
This is a really generic question as to almost anybody that I ask is like,

00:14:53.719 --> 00:14:57.880
how does one do this optimally or is there an optimal way?

00:15:00.679 --> 00:15:05.719
That's a really good question. And it's something I spent a ton of time thinking through conceptually

00:15:05.719 --> 00:15:10.280
when I joined the organization. I was the first dedicated business analytics hire. And so

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:16.359
I was also joining as a team of one. So finite resource in that respect.

00:15:17.479 --> 00:15:23.239
I don't know if this is best practice, but the sort of what I ended up doing is I essentially

00:15:23.239 --> 00:15:30.280
developed three criteria and a little checklist that would allow me to have that scoping exercise

00:15:30.280 --> 00:15:36.359
that you referenced. And really what that scoping exercise boiled down to is sort of

00:15:36.359 --> 00:15:43.159
what's the size of the prize or what's the size of the problem? Two, do we actually have data

00:15:43.159 --> 00:15:51.239
that can help understand or improve the problem? And then three, when does the work need to be

00:15:51.239 --> 00:15:56.280
done? What's the timing? And by focusing on those three problems,

00:15:57.080 --> 00:16:04.280
gotten pretty adept at filtering projects that are material enough that sort of warrant

00:16:04.280 --> 00:16:09.159
a significant investment of time. Two, that we can actually influence through thinking about

00:16:09.159 --> 00:16:14.520
through a data science or analytical perspective. And three, fits with the business cadence.

00:16:15.159 --> 00:16:19.559
And if you sort of strike out or can't check all three of those boxes, then you

00:16:20.679 --> 00:16:26.280
facilitate the next conversation of like, okay, I can't directly help you, but how can we move

00:16:26.280 --> 00:16:33.320
this forward? And I'll candidly, particularly when I initially joined, you have some uncomfortable

00:16:33.320 --> 00:16:38.760
conversations because as a service function and a support resource, having to tell your colleagues

00:16:38.760 --> 00:16:45.159
that I can't directly help you, or here's why this may not be a good fit. Those are tough

00:16:45.159 --> 00:16:53.400
conversations to have, but I think necessary conversations that you can prioritize your time

00:16:53.400 --> 00:16:55.080
on day-to-day for your business.

00:17:00.919 --> 00:17:06.359
Thanks, Chase. And Libby, I see you just asked a question in the chat as well, if you

00:17:06.359 --> 00:17:08.760
want to jump in and ask that one.

00:17:10.760 --> 00:17:17.479
Sure. Yeah. I was wondering about dynamic, like real-time dynamic pricing models for tickets.

00:17:17.479 --> 00:17:20.359
That's something that I've always been really interested in as a person who does like

00:17:20.359 --> 00:17:25.160
optimization and stuff like that. But I don't know how widespread that actually is. And I was

00:17:25.160 --> 00:17:30.040
wondering how the pandemic might have shifted some of those models for sports teams.

00:17:31.239 --> 00:17:39.400
Yeah. So dynamic pricing, it's a big topic and a huge area of focus. As an organization,

00:17:39.400 --> 00:17:47.079
I believe we began adopting dynamic pricing in 2011 or 2012. So we've got roughly a decade

00:17:47.319 --> 00:17:53.560
under our belt. I will say I would draw a big distinction in how we think about dynamic pricing

00:17:53.560 --> 00:17:58.839
versus someone like a leading e-commerce store, someone like an Amazon, where they've got millions

00:17:58.839 --> 00:18:04.839
of SKUs and they have some humans behind the scenes. But they've deployed machine learning

00:18:04.839 --> 00:18:11.239
models to sort of algorithmically price and manipulate prices in a somewhat automated

00:18:11.239 --> 00:18:17.800
fashion. We are not that hands-off. So behind the scenes, there's a collaboration between myself

00:18:17.800 --> 00:18:23.479
and our ticketing colleagues. And we're essentially in real-time, always monitoring and observing

00:18:25.160 --> 00:18:30.040
demand as it materializes. We have some analytical models that help us

00:18:32.520 --> 00:18:39.719
make some estimates on how we may change price. But it is a little more sort of manual and hands-on

00:18:39.719 --> 00:18:45.400
than at least in an academic setting, when you think about this is the optimal dynamic pricing

00:18:45.959 --> 00:18:51.800
infrastructure, where we've got some real headroom to sort of grow into that type of model.

00:18:53.719 --> 00:18:57.319
I think that's great. Thank you. Yeah. I think keeping the human in the loop,

00:18:57.319 --> 00:19:04.040
like the algorithm loop, is really interesting. And also kind of the algorithm aversion that you

00:19:04.040 --> 00:19:07.640
might see, where you're like, oh, I don't think that's the right thing to do. I don't want the

00:19:07.640 --> 00:19:13.160
computer to make the decision for me. That's been an interesting topic. And I think that it's great

00:19:13.160 --> 00:19:18.839
that you guys use it as a reference and not as something that's automatic. Yeah. I think part

00:19:18.839 --> 00:19:26.040
of this, I think, is the sports industry. There's two dynamics that sort of distinguish us from a

00:19:26.040 --> 00:19:32.599
lot of other dynamic pricing applications. One, we have finite inventory. We've got 41,000 seats

00:19:32.599 --> 00:19:39.400
per event. And two, that inventory expires and becomes perishable. So I can't sell a ticket to

00:19:39.400 --> 00:19:47.079
last Tuesday's game. And then the third part of that is, in addition, we have multiple sales

00:19:47.079 --> 00:19:53.560
channels. And so accurately, you can get some interesting signals in your data that may or may

00:19:53.560 --> 00:19:58.839
not actually correlate to an increase or decrease in demand. So for example, a large group ticket

00:19:58.839 --> 00:20:03.719
in order, if there is a church group or some, we may sell a chunk of 500 tickets

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:10.520
without some proper treatment and nuanced understanding of how that data actually

00:20:10.520 --> 00:20:16.280
flows through our systems. You could make the naive interpretation of demand is through the

00:20:16.280 --> 00:20:22.040
roof, no change price. And that may or may not actually have anything to do with the underlying

00:20:22.040 --> 00:20:30.920
demand as just like when a group sale closed, for example. I have a similar question to Robert,

00:20:30.920 --> 00:20:35.400
who just put in the chat. Should we use incognito mode when purchasing sports tickets?

00:20:36.040 --> 00:20:42.839
I've always wondered that for concerts. I mean, I would say this is more my personal bias. I think

00:20:42.839 --> 00:20:46.199
you should probably use incognito for most of the things that you do on the internet.

00:20:46.920 --> 00:20:53.800
And I would say that probably extends to purchasing sports tickets. No, I mean,

00:20:53.800 --> 00:20:59.319
I think both through our official primary channel, you know, clubs.com slash tickets, we have a

00:21:00.439 --> 00:21:06.839
decently robust ad tech stack behind the scenes that will allow us to sort of track

00:21:06.839 --> 00:21:14.119
your behavior to some extent and then, you know, showing you relevant ads or sort of follow up to

00:21:14.119 --> 00:21:21.160
that. You know, certainly if you look at the secondary markets, those organizations have

00:21:21.719 --> 00:21:29.160
very robust ad tech stacks that I'm somewhat envious of because that's central to the

00:21:29.160 --> 00:21:32.040
success of their business and they've made the necessary investments.

00:21:35.479 --> 00:21:40.199
Can you tell us like buy tickets X days before? Just kidding.

00:21:41.160 --> 00:21:47.959
No, I mean, that's an interesting what people do. We have seen a huge shift of people delaying

00:21:47.959 --> 00:21:54.359
their purchase closer and closer to events. And so that's a consumer behavior phenomena that we're

00:21:54.359 --> 00:21:58.359
seeing across all sorts of industries. I think that creates a risk for us as a business, going

00:21:58.359 --> 00:22:05.640
back to my point related to expiring inventory. So as sales get pushed closer and closer to the

00:22:05.640 --> 00:22:11.719
event date, that just creates more uncertainty for our business. And we spend a lot of time

00:22:12.359 --> 00:22:16.359
thinking about how do we sort of operate in this environment that we're watching unfold.

00:22:18.839 --> 00:22:24.119
Right. I see an anonymous question that just came in that was, since sports games happen

00:22:24.119 --> 00:22:30.119
so frequently, how are models and analytical projects evaluated over what time period?

00:22:30.520 --> 00:22:40.520
I'd say it's highly context specific. In baseball, there's a couple lenses that most of our decisions

00:22:40.520 --> 00:22:48.199
sort of naturally fall into. One is a yearly cadence. To some extent, the baseball schedule

00:22:48.199 --> 00:22:54.520
was pretty much set in stone from April 1st to the end of September. And so a lot of the work

00:22:54.680 --> 00:23:00.680
that we do, the true and sort of final evaluations for success, certainly sort of materializes

00:23:00.680 --> 00:23:05.719
throughout the season, but the real evaluation is after the season has unfolded. More at the

00:23:05.719 --> 00:23:12.920
operational level, there is success that can be evaluated and changes actually put in practice,

00:23:13.719 --> 00:23:20.680
sometimes on a game to game basis, but more often than not, a homestand by homestand basis.

00:23:21.160 --> 00:23:25.319
A homestand by homestand basis. And so it's roughly every other week,

00:23:25.880 --> 00:23:30.359
so we can make operational changes. The team goes away for 10 days,

00:23:30.359 --> 00:23:33.560
and then they come back. And so we can make some changes in between homestands.

00:23:37.479 --> 00:23:42.439
Thank you. Mubanga, I see you had, I think, a follow-up question maybe to what

00:23:42.439 --> 00:23:45.959
Libby had asked earlier. Did you want to jump in and ask that?

00:23:50.680 --> 00:24:01.959
Or we can get back to that one after. I wasn't sure how to summarize the question in there. But

00:24:03.560 --> 00:24:06.680
I see there's also an anonymous question for you, Chase, that was...

00:24:06.680 --> 00:24:12.199
Sorry, Rachel, I was on mute. So that was basically a comment based on what

00:24:13.239 --> 00:24:19.560
Chase explained in reaction to Libby's question, because I was just thinking to myself,

00:24:21.160 --> 00:24:28.359
because the pricing is dynamic, so it means that the system is changing continuously in time.

00:24:28.359 --> 00:24:31.959
So I've seen applications before where reinforcement learning has been used in

00:24:33.479 --> 00:24:37.719
not exactly the same setting, but in settings like that, like self-driving cars, for example.

00:24:38.680 --> 00:24:44.280
So I was just wondering to myself, what kind of algorithm they use at the Cubs?

00:24:44.280 --> 00:24:59.000
So I would say, so specific to dynamic pricing, we have tested a wide range of different

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:05.239
algorithms, sort of decision frameworks, everything from your traditional classic

00:25:05.959 --> 00:25:13.880
regression-based models to non-parametric models. Jeff and I, in our prior life, worked at a

00:25:14.359 --> 00:25:19.000
consulting shop that specialized in a variety of Bayesian techniques. And so I've

00:25:21.160 --> 00:25:27.400
messed around and tried to make the Bayesian frameworks fit within the type of data that we

00:25:27.400 --> 00:25:37.000
have. I will say, having spent a fair amount of time in that area, I think the bigger challenge

00:25:37.079 --> 00:25:44.119
that we have is more at the data synthesis and aggregation layer, getting the various

00:25:44.760 --> 00:25:50.040
data sets that you would want in real time or sort of at the right granularity or frequency

00:25:50.040 --> 00:25:56.359
that we ideally want to make decisions. We run into more bottlenecks at that layer versus any

00:25:56.359 --> 00:26:01.640
individual algorithm will end up being somewhat performance, given the data constraints that we

00:26:01.640 --> 00:26:08.280
have. So I spend more of my time focused at how can I go get the incremental data at a more fine

00:26:09.640 --> 00:26:14.199
granularity so that we could sort of more meaningfully engage in more of the

00:26:15.079 --> 00:26:18.280
sort of true optimization, algorithm optimization.

00:26:22.520 --> 00:26:27.079
Thanks, Chase. I see Jeff asked another question in the chat that was,

00:26:27.079 --> 00:26:31.719
is there any animosity between the Cubs and resellers like Ticketmaster?

00:26:36.119 --> 00:26:43.000
It's a good question. So in the ticket distribution space, you've got a couple

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:48.040
different entities. You have us as the Cubs, and we sell on our own channels, right? You go to the

00:26:48.040 --> 00:26:53.000
box office, you can call a call phone number, cubs.com slash tickets. Then you have the secondary

00:26:53.000 --> 00:27:00.199
markets. But you also have the different terms are used, but brokers, essentially people who are

00:27:00.199 --> 00:27:05.880
in the business of acquiring inventory from us and then selling those tickets in a variety

00:27:08.040 --> 00:27:15.160
through a variety of channels. I think there is some healthy tension that can arise because the

00:27:15.160 --> 00:27:21.160
sort of the incentives that each of those parties have may not always align with one another.

00:27:23.319 --> 00:27:29.640
And so in general, I think our incentives are pretty aligned with the secondary exchanges

00:27:29.640 --> 00:27:35.079
themselves. We want to have the sort of the broadest distribution pipes that we can and

00:27:35.079 --> 00:27:40.439
sort of get our tickets in front of people sort of wherever they are and however they want to

00:27:40.439 --> 00:27:46.119
purchase. Those exchanges, they're obviously interested in helping to sell Cubs tickets,

00:27:46.119 --> 00:27:50.839
but they have a huge portfolio of live event inventory that they also care about.

00:27:51.800 --> 00:27:55.880
So there's just, we haven't, I don't think we've perfected the business model or sort of the

00:27:55.880 --> 00:28:03.079
relationship between all of the various parties. But in general, we work pretty well together.

00:28:07.719 --> 00:28:13.719
Thank you. And apologies, my audio just got a little cut out for a second. So let me know if

00:28:13.800 --> 00:28:21.239
it sounds weird to anyone. But I think I missed a question earlier, Sep, that you had asked,

00:28:21.239 --> 00:28:26.760
and sorry if I missed any other questions earlier too, but can I pass the mic over to you for that

00:28:26.760 --> 00:28:33.560
one? Yeah, sure. So I think you had referred to your, someone asked a question about your tech

00:28:33.560 --> 00:28:38.839
stack earlier, but I kind of wanted to understand a little bit of that last mile of how you deliver

00:28:39.400 --> 00:28:50.680
your results to the business. Yeah, so I'd say a couple avenues. We build and maintain a small

00:28:50.680 --> 00:28:56.920
number of Shiny applications, which ends up being sort of a deliverable. A fair number of outputs

00:28:56.920 --> 00:29:04.839
will be injected back into our data warehouse and then rendered through our BI layer. But also,

00:29:04.839 --> 00:29:10.439
I'll admit, at least for our business, a lot of my counterparts across the organization still

00:29:10.439 --> 00:29:16.599
rely pretty heavily on effectively the Microsoft stacks. It's Excel, it's PowerPoint, it's Word.

00:29:17.640 --> 00:29:26.599
And it's been a big ambition of mine to get away from that mindset, but it's a real reality. And

00:29:26.599 --> 00:29:33.319
part of it is a lot of the outputs that we generate make their way into other source

00:29:33.319 --> 00:29:39.479
documents or deliverables that I don't own or sort of have much purview into. Certainly,

00:29:40.680 --> 00:29:46.040
board materials, if we're putting a board deck or a memo together,

00:29:47.239 --> 00:29:51.880
need to provide deliverables that can easily be dropped and moved in those documents.

00:29:55.319 --> 00:30:01.880
Thanks. Can I dive a bit deeper there? Because I'm sure that a bunch of people on the call have

00:30:01.880 --> 00:30:12.280
that struggle as well. How are you going about trying to change that or working together with

00:30:12.280 --> 00:30:20.839
the team? I'm not sure I have a great answer. I think what, internally, I am making a conscious

00:30:20.839 --> 00:30:28.839
effort to shift more and more of our deliverables into more reproducible R Markdown or just sort of

00:30:28.839 --> 00:30:35.880
fully contained scripts and processes and then sort of go kicking and screaming when we need to

00:30:35.880 --> 00:30:45.319
break that paradigm. But that's, it's a constant sort of tension or something that we're always

00:30:45.319 --> 00:30:56.119
evaluating. So, with R Markdown, does the team also generate PowerPoint or Word from R Markdown

00:30:56.119 --> 00:31:04.040
too? I have tried to be honest, given, and this is sort of in the weeds on the specific formats and

00:31:04.839 --> 00:31:12.520
sort of the preferences that we have in those templates, I haven't been able to fully close

00:31:12.520 --> 00:31:20.599
the gap and get sort of 100% continuity there. I'm sure it could be done. It's more of a timing

00:31:20.599 --> 00:31:27.560
and resourcing thing. Yeah, that's something I hear a lot from like the Excel reports perspective

00:31:27.560 --> 00:31:34.599
too, like around certain formatting. Tatiana, I see you had a question you just asked in the

00:31:34.599 --> 00:31:43.800
chat as well. Would you want to ask that one live? Sure. So, you did mention, Chase, that you deal

00:31:43.800 --> 00:31:49.400
with ambiguity and uncertainty a lot. So, I'd be curious to hear what are your most go-to techniques

00:31:49.400 --> 00:31:53.560
for approaching ambiguity and where do you basically stop and say, hey, this is the threshold

00:31:53.560 --> 00:31:58.680
where I'm about to accept it and I'm not going to dig further. And the second question was just

00:31:58.680 --> 00:32:04.680
about your journey since you started on as a one-man department. How did your role evolve and

00:32:04.680 --> 00:32:10.040
what aspect did you enjoy most from business analysis to data science? It seems like you're

00:32:10.040 --> 00:32:15.719
more into data science right now and I'm curious to hear how it started. Yeah, both good

00:32:15.719 --> 00:32:22.520
questions. I'll try and I'll take them in order. So, in thinking about uncertainty,

00:32:23.959 --> 00:32:29.719
I think there's two questions. There's two questions embedded in there. One is more

00:32:29.719 --> 00:32:37.640
the mechanically how do you think about and actually quantify the uncertainty from an

00:32:37.640 --> 00:32:43.800
analytical perspective. And I'd go back to a lot of the Bayesian frameworks that I was introduced

00:32:43.880 --> 00:32:51.640
to in my first job. They've just got some nice academically rigorous and just like

00:32:51.640 --> 00:32:56.520
conceptually sound manners to actually to think about confidence intervals or credible intervals.

00:32:56.520 --> 00:33:03.400
And so, I use those frameworks sort of mechanically. I think where I have spent a lot of time is getting

00:33:03.400 --> 00:33:08.520
my colleagues and counterparts in our organization comfortable with embracing that uncertainty.

00:33:09.079 --> 00:33:16.040
A lot of the areas where I spend my time, we have to our analytical

00:33:16.040 --> 00:33:21.160
deliverables are due several weeks or months in advance of those events actually

00:33:21.160 --> 00:33:25.880
happening. And so, to sit here in the first week of November and

00:33:25.880 --> 00:33:31.800
with 100% specificity say here's my projection for the ticket sales next July,

00:33:33.239 --> 00:33:38.040
it's really hard to make an argument. But I've spent a lot of time getting our organization

00:33:38.040 --> 00:33:42.199
understand like here's the range of probable outcomes. Here are the things that would make

00:33:42.199 --> 00:33:49.800
us believe that we may over index or sort of underperform. And how much risk or uncertainty

00:33:49.800 --> 00:33:56.920
are we willing to accept and sort of what's the downside of if we misproject or basically

00:33:56.920 --> 00:34:03.239
what's the cost of being wrong. And that's taken the better part of my five years here to

00:34:03.880 --> 00:34:10.840
sort of get folks to fully embrace. COVID-19 was somewhat beneficial in that because we had

00:34:10.840 --> 00:34:17.320
so much uncertainty facing our business. It was front and center and there was no other way,

00:34:17.320 --> 00:34:21.879
at least in my opinion, to like reasonably think about what may happen in our business than through

00:34:22.840 --> 00:34:29.479
sort of a truly probabilistic manner. I'm sorry, your second question was more on

00:34:29.879 --> 00:34:38.360
how your role basically evolved, but going back to uncertainty for a second. So, you basically,

00:34:38.360 --> 00:34:43.000
you first build out your model and then you accept stakeholders. So, you consult them on

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:46.520
what level of uncertainty they're willing to accept or do you set it beforehand and you

00:34:46.520 --> 00:34:53.879
have a conversation like here's my data, here's how far we can go and here's the levels of

00:34:53.879 --> 00:34:58.919
uncertainty we can dig into. Is that the conversation you have beforehand or after

00:34:58.919 --> 00:35:08.199
you build your model or it depends? And to some extent, it depends. I try and

00:35:09.800 --> 00:35:17.000
before materially engaging with colleagues, I try and get sort of push the analytical models as far

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:23.080
as we can. So, I have an understanding on here's how much sort of statistical power, how confident

00:35:23.080 --> 00:35:29.479
we can be in these results and then also framing up, you know, we are getting into the grounds of

00:35:29.479 --> 00:35:34.199
like I don't have, we don't have specific enough data or they're just more uncertainty. You're sort

00:35:34.199 --> 00:35:38.520
of crossing a threshold of we're asking for precision that this model can't really support.

00:35:40.120 --> 00:35:45.959
So, let's take a step back and sort of understand what those limits are. Does that answer your

00:35:45.959 --> 00:35:50.280
question? Yeah, kind of does because there's no, like it's hard to answer a vague question, right?

00:35:50.280 --> 00:35:56.600
So, yeah. And the second question was about just your role, how it evolved. I assume that

00:35:56.600 --> 00:36:02.360
since you were the first person, right, as far as I understand it in your analytics

00:36:03.800 --> 00:36:10.439
department in your company, how much did you have to spend on the buy-in and business analysis,

00:36:10.439 --> 00:36:19.560
etc. Or if the stage that the company was in when you joined them was, I guess, cognizant enough

00:36:20.280 --> 00:36:25.639
of the processes so you didn't have to spend a lot of time on educating, I guess. And which

00:36:25.639 --> 00:36:31.879
aspect did you enjoy most as your role? Yeah, so when I joined, there was a, the organization had

00:36:31.879 --> 00:36:38.040
to recognize the need to bring on some more resources in the business analytics area. So,

00:36:38.040 --> 00:36:42.520
there was a little bit of initial buy-in that had already sort of occurred that led to

00:36:43.639 --> 00:36:49.959
my role being created. You know, having said that, in any organization, you're ultimately building

00:36:49.959 --> 00:36:55.800
relationships with individuals. And so, I was pretty conscious in finding some quick lens and

00:36:55.800 --> 00:37:02.360
sort of, you know, early victories that I could find to gain that credibility so that we could

00:37:02.360 --> 00:37:12.439
grow into bigger, more complex and challenging problems. When I joined, I'd say most of the

00:37:12.439 --> 00:37:17.080
problems that I initially worked on in the first 12 to 18 months were sort of pretty pure point

00:37:17.080 --> 00:37:22.600
analytics. Like, the problems were well-defined and scoped. There was a clear analytical angle

00:37:22.600 --> 00:37:28.439
that we could bring to the table, but it was, you know, pretty well boxed. As I have progressed

00:37:28.439 --> 00:37:34.760
through my five years here, more and more of the work that I spend on, where I spend my time now,

00:37:34.760 --> 00:37:40.360
is addressing bigger strategic issues for the organization and sort of, somewhat major sort of

00:37:40.360 --> 00:37:49.159
policy decisions that we are evaluating. And I certainly own and sort of bring the consumer

00:37:49.159 --> 00:37:55.800
and the data perspective to the table, but there are very real sort of non-quantitative

00:37:55.800 --> 00:38:01.000
other stakeholders and other considerations that, as an organization, we need to evaluate. And we have,

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:06.120
you know, a very large media presence as an organization. And so, we're very conscious of

00:38:06.679 --> 00:38:13.719
the messages that we put in the market and sort of our standing just from a PR standpoint.

00:38:13.719 --> 00:38:18.919
I've not figured out how to weave that into my analytical models, but that it's a very real

00:38:18.919 --> 00:38:25.479
consideration that, you know, it's more of an open discussion and dialogue with my colleagues.

00:38:29.479 --> 00:38:35.639
Thank you. I see Robert had also asked earlier, what does collaboration look like

00:38:35.639 --> 00:38:42.840
with various vendors that the CUB uses? And then Libby kind of had a plus one to that,

00:38:42.840 --> 00:38:46.520
that asks, are vendors connected in any way as far as data sharing,

00:38:47.399 --> 00:38:55.080
like from a connected supply chain perspective? So, I guess, Libby, do you mind helping me

00:38:55.080 --> 00:39:00.520
understand the second part of your question in a little bit more detail? I could go in a couple

00:39:00.520 --> 00:39:08.040
different directions there. Sure. So, I was wondering if the CUBs have visibility into the

00:39:08.040 --> 00:39:13.959
data of suppliers or vendors, and if that goes the other direction as well, if it's even present.

00:39:15.879 --> 00:39:20.520
I guess, sorry, I keep diving in here. Are you thinking sort of specifically in consumer type

00:39:20.520 --> 00:39:26.520
data or more just other, like, operational business data that we need to create?

00:39:27.399 --> 00:39:33.479
Ah, so I would say a little bit of both, whether that's information about your consumers that are

00:39:33.479 --> 00:39:40.280
coming from vendors who might be servicing ticket sales, or if it's more of a supply type thing

00:39:40.280 --> 00:39:46.439
where you guys have, you know, business suppliers, do they have visibility into your supply chain,

00:39:46.439 --> 00:39:49.719
or do you have visibility upstream or downstream in that sort of sense of the word?

00:39:50.600 --> 00:39:58.760
Yeah. Okay. Thank you. Super helpful. So, I guess a couple parts of that, the main driver of

00:39:58.760 --> 00:40:05.399
customer data are ticket sales. So, we have sort of complete visibility into the ticket sale

00:40:06.120 --> 00:40:12.760
process. We have, four or five years ago, we began delivering all of our tickets

00:40:13.879 --> 00:40:19.080
globally, so you can no longer print a ticket. You don't get a hard stack ticket. You can't do,

00:40:19.080 --> 00:40:24.439
like, print at home PDF thing anymore. So, through that, we're generating a lot of data,

00:40:25.080 --> 00:40:28.760
right? So, now we get ticket forward data, and so we get more insight into

00:40:30.840 --> 00:40:38.600
sort of who is actually attending a game. And the next evolution of that, that we unroll for

00:40:38.600 --> 00:40:45.479
2021 is through our mobile ordering footprint. Now we can actually tie individual, now we've

00:40:45.479 --> 00:40:51.399
got pretty good insight into the ticket data. Now, for the people who leverage our mobile

00:40:51.399 --> 00:40:55.560
ordering platform, now I can actually start to understand food and beverage preferences

00:40:55.560 --> 00:40:59.719
about that individual, which we've never had insight into before, right? Historically,

00:40:59.719 --> 00:41:03.639
you'd go to the concession stand, you'd buy whatever you buy. We get, like, the last four

00:41:03.639 --> 00:41:11.479
of the credit card, but no meaningful way to tie that back to any individual. So, that's been sort

00:41:11.479 --> 00:41:17.399
of the main sources of data. We also own our own Wi-Fi deployment, so we generate some customer

00:41:17.399 --> 00:41:24.360
data there. You know, we do have, obviously, we spend a, we have a decent footprint in terms of

00:41:24.360 --> 00:41:29.320
digital spend across the social media websites, and so, you know, we kind of fit into probably

00:41:29.320 --> 00:41:34.840
their, like, small and medium business category, but we have active, you know, engagement and

00:41:34.840 --> 00:41:41.080
collaboration with them to sort of improve our marketing operations, basically.

00:41:45.159 --> 00:41:50.120
Thanks, Chase. I know that some of the, like, R and sports analytics meetups,

00:41:50.120 --> 00:41:57.000
a lot of people have questions around how to, like, get that first job in sports. I'm curious

00:41:57.000 --> 00:42:02.679
to hear your perspective there on maybe how you do that or how you'd advise others to go about that.

00:42:03.560 --> 00:42:10.040
Yeah, so I think finding the first job in sports is often the most challenging one. I think once

00:42:10.040 --> 00:42:16.199
you've found a foothold, it's a pretty, particularly on the business side, it's pretty open and sort of

00:42:16.199 --> 00:42:21.879
collaborative community, and so you see a fair amount of, not job hopping, but you can sort of

00:42:21.879 --> 00:42:28.760
navigate the professional team landscape somewhat, I won't say easily, but it happens quite a bit.

00:42:29.719 --> 00:42:35.719
In terms of putting together a strategy to land that first job in sports, I'd highlight a couple

00:42:35.719 --> 00:42:41.959
things. One, I'd go back to sort of where I started. If your preference and priority is

00:42:41.959 --> 00:42:48.840
to work in sort of the baseball or the player operations side of the house, there's a pretty

00:42:48.840 --> 00:42:55.800
clear path of developing some expertise in being incredibly smart and sophisticated and understanding

00:42:55.800 --> 00:43:02.040
player performance. On the business side, at least for me, I had really no understanding of

00:43:02.040 --> 00:43:06.360
how the business of baseball worked before I got into the business, but there's some good

00:43:06.360 --> 00:43:10.679
publicly available resources for not only baseball but all the major sports. I think Forbes does a

00:43:10.679 --> 00:43:17.000
really good job of just synthesizing, here's how the business side of these operations work, and so

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:23.639
I'd spend some time just level setting and really understanding how businesses operate.

00:43:24.199 --> 00:43:30.600
The second focus I have is you need to get a little scrappy and tap into your network and

00:43:30.600 --> 00:43:36.919
find friends or friends of friends, reach out on LinkedIn or if you Google

00:43:36.919 --> 00:43:41.800
Cubs front office or any team front office, you'll find sort of the full, in general, find the full

00:43:41.800 --> 00:43:47.080
roster of employees. So look at the job descriptions, look at the titles, look at the individuals,

00:43:47.080 --> 00:43:55.959
reach out, start to build some connections. The third one is be patient. In general, we are,

00:43:56.679 --> 00:44:01.959
all front offices are smaller than maybe most people would think, and so jobs don't necessarily

00:44:01.959 --> 00:44:09.719
have a predictable hiring cadence, and so be patient and do some diligence to figure out

00:44:10.199 --> 00:44:16.679
when jobs do become available. And the last thing I'd highlight is

00:44:17.239 --> 00:44:21.159
if your heart is set on working for a front office, I'm certainly not going to tell you to

00:44:21.159 --> 00:44:26.919
not go down that path, but there are some awesome jobs available in what I'd say the front office

00:44:26.919 --> 00:44:32.919
adjacent industries. The major concessionaires all employ hundreds of thousands of

00:44:33.479 --> 00:44:38.679
not hundreds of thousands, but hundreds of analytics focused professionals. There's a great

00:44:38.679 --> 00:44:43.560
sort of cottage industry of consultants that focus on the sports space, so depending on your

00:44:43.560 --> 00:44:50.360
preferences and priorities, you can land a job in any number of sort of sport adjacent

00:44:52.439 --> 00:44:59.320
areas. So the last thing I'll say is a little bit self-serving here, but I am looking to add a

00:44:59.320 --> 00:45:04.840
couple folks to my team. We've got one job description up right now and another will be up

00:45:04.840 --> 00:45:11.479
shortly, so if anyone's interested in focusing on improving the business operations,

00:45:11.479 --> 00:45:17.080
cubs.com slash jobs, and there we've got some opportunities available on our team.

00:45:19.479 --> 00:45:26.280
Awesome. Something that might be helpful to dive into deeper here, and maybe with the whole group

00:45:26.280 --> 00:45:32.600
as well, is when we talk about like being able to find these opportunities and networking,

00:45:32.600 --> 00:45:39.159
I wonder how like finding a diverse pool of candidates also plays into that, and what are

00:45:39.159 --> 00:45:49.239
some of the things that your organization does? Yeah, it's a challenge. You know, we are

00:45:49.879 --> 00:45:58.840
making a very conscious effort to try and raise the brand awareness and profile of our organization

00:45:58.840 --> 00:46:08.919
to groups who may not otherwise naturally find cubs.com slash jobs. The tactics on how you

00:46:08.919 --> 00:46:18.040
execute that are somewhat specific to the individual roles, but it's a big emphasis

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:27.479
and priority for us as an organization that I think we had. It's just an area that we can

00:46:27.479 --> 00:46:32.520
get better and evolve, and so it's making conscious efforts to increase sort of the

00:46:32.520 --> 00:46:38.040
top of the funnel. How do we raise our brand awareness and footprint so that we can attract a

00:46:39.639 --> 00:46:47.719
more qualified and diverse group of candidates? It's something that we're spending a lot of time

00:46:47.800 --> 00:46:58.120
trying to evolve and get better at. That's great. Thank you. I see there was another

00:46:59.080 --> 00:47:05.719
anonymous question earlier that asked about what you originally studied. Was it analytics, or

00:47:05.719 --> 00:47:13.320
how did you get into this space? So my undergrad work focused on political science and psychology,

00:47:13.639 --> 00:47:21.159
so not terribly heavy on the data analytics front. My first job, I feel like I got the

00:47:21.159 --> 00:47:27.239
equivalent of a master's in applied statistics, so a lot of on-the-job training. I supplemented

00:47:27.239 --> 00:47:34.280
that with some graduate coursework in statistics, and then I went back and did my MBA part-time

00:47:35.080 --> 00:47:41.719
with a focus on operations analytics and marketing, but I'd say most of my practical,

00:47:42.280 --> 00:47:44.919
what I use in my day-to-day really came from my first job.

00:47:46.679 --> 00:47:52.760
And so are there certain skills that you're hiring for right now, or certain things that

00:47:52.760 --> 00:48:00.520
you're looking for for those open roles? I would say yes. So one, just so we're looking to bring

00:48:00.520 --> 00:48:05.000
on a pricing analyst, someone to help us get smarter on sort of all the things that we talked

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:09.479
about previously with respect to pricing, and the second role is more database marketing and sales

00:48:09.479 --> 00:48:20.040
operations focused. I think in terms of skills, I think I need someone to be successful in these

00:48:20.040 --> 00:48:25.000
roles in particular, and I think this does apply to a lot of analytics-focused roles in sports,

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:31.159
is you need to be comfortable with wearing a couple different hats. I am not a database engineer

00:48:31.159 --> 00:48:37.639
by trade, but nonetheless, unlike working at a big tech company where you've got seemingly

00:48:37.639 --> 00:48:43.399
unlimited resources and people can get incredibly hyper-focused and specific on very interesting

00:48:43.399 --> 00:48:47.719
and niche problems, we need someone who is a little bit more of a generalist and comfortable

00:48:47.719 --> 00:48:54.439
wearing a couple different hats. And so people who have backgrounds in statistics, who have

00:48:54.439 --> 00:49:02.600
sat in the chair at another company, sport adjacent is super helpful. I think the other

00:49:02.600 --> 00:49:08.840
thing that, interesting contrast between my first role as a consultant and what I, what I, in my

00:49:08.840 --> 00:49:15.639
current chair is, we, I get to sort of wear the consulting hat, but we're also the operator, and so

00:49:17.080 --> 00:49:22.840
there's a much bigger emphasis and focus on practical analytics that we can actually deploy,

00:49:24.199 --> 00:49:29.000
whereas at least in my previous role as a consultant, we got to do all this super interesting

00:49:29.239 --> 00:49:34.199
and fun analytical work, but ultimately you kind of hand that over to the client, and then you, you go

00:49:34.199 --> 00:49:39.719
on to the next project. We have the burden of actually putting into practice what we, what we

00:49:39.719 --> 00:49:45.159
build, and so having, you know, more of the mindset and sort of wanting to take ownership of the full

00:49:45.879 --> 00:49:53.080
analytical process end-to-end, which is a little bit different than what, at least when I went

00:49:53.080 --> 00:49:57.399
through school, there wasn't a ton of focus on that last part of like, how do you actually move

00:49:57.399 --> 00:50:06.199
a business forward through the application of analytics? Yeah. Russ, I see you just asked a

00:50:06.199 --> 00:50:12.760
question. I'd love to turn that over to you to, to ask, Clive. Yeah, thanks, Rachel. Chase, love,

00:50:12.760 --> 00:50:19.239
love the content so far. You know, one thing, you know, that affects a lot of us that work in

00:50:19.239 --> 00:50:26.360
financial services are systematic shifts in data, right? So think about something like COVID,

00:50:26.360 --> 00:50:31.879
right, drastically affected consumer buying behavior, and it really wasn't something we had

00:50:31.879 --> 00:50:38.439
seen historically, you know, in our data lakes and data warehouses, right? So certainly complicated

00:50:38.439 --> 00:50:43.959
my job and my team's job a lot, because a lot of our models were misfiring pretty, pretty badly,

00:50:43.959 --> 00:50:47.800
right? And I think, you know, sports analytics has always been something that's been very

00:50:47.800 --> 00:50:52.600
interesting to me, like full disclosure, Cleveland Indians fan or Guardians fan, so I still haven't

00:50:52.600 --> 00:50:58.679
gotten over 2016 yet. You know, I've been fascinated by like ESPN's FPI, and some of the

00:50:58.679 --> 00:51:03.159
stuff they do in Georgia Tech related to college basketball, but I'm thinking about specifically

00:51:03.159 --> 00:51:07.639
with the Cubs, right, and sort of like the transitional state they're in, in the organization,

00:51:08.199 --> 00:51:15.320
specifically, you know, trading way, Schwarber and Baez, and, you know, I forget the gentleman

00:51:15.320 --> 00:51:21.080
went to San Francisco, but I would have to imagine that's going to make a lot of your historical

00:51:21.080 --> 00:51:27.320
data a little less useful for you and your team. Do you have any tips or strategies, or have you

00:51:27.320 --> 00:51:31.800
guys started, you know, digging into this and seeing what you can do to sort of like make your

00:51:32.520 --> 00:51:38.280
maybe previous models better fitting for the new reality you guys are going to be in?

00:51:39.399 --> 00:51:47.639
Yeah, that's a great question. You sort of hit on the fundamental crux of what I think it means to

00:51:47.639 --> 00:51:55.560
sit on the business side of a sports organization, somewhat in an abstract sense. All teams, sports

00:51:55.560 --> 00:51:59.879
are cyclical by nature, right, and that's due to a variety of reasons, mostly a lot of it's

00:51:59.879 --> 00:52:05.879
team performance related. Our job on the business side is to smooth out those natural team performance

00:52:05.879 --> 00:52:12.600
cycles, and, you know, when team performance is really good, our job is to push the business

00:52:12.600 --> 00:52:16.840
forward, and then when team performance takes a step back, like we just saw at the most recent

00:52:16.840 --> 00:52:22.199
trade deadline, it's to sort of mitigate the loss or put a, you know, don't let the floor go as low,

00:52:23.320 --> 00:52:28.760
and so our job is to mitigate sort of that natural team performance cycle and

00:52:30.120 --> 00:52:34.679
move the business forward, somewhat independent of where we're at in any given team performance

00:52:34.679 --> 00:52:39.719
or competitive dynamic cycle. That's the abstract answer, and that's sort of, that's my like

00:52:40.280 --> 00:52:46.840
and how I think about how I can impact the business. More mechanically, to your point,

00:52:48.120 --> 00:52:53.800
we are in a drastically different demand environment and just sort of team performance

00:52:53.800 --> 00:53:00.760
cycle today than we were even four months ago. What I have done from a practical standpoint is,

00:53:00.760 --> 00:53:07.800
you know, we have pretty good historical data, and if you go back to 2010, 11, 12, 13, 14, the

00:53:07.879 --> 00:53:14.280
Cubs were not terribly competitive, and so I have, what I, what we have done is put a little

00:53:14.280 --> 00:53:23.560
bit more emphasis on more further back in time, but data and demand profiles, that is a little

00:53:23.560 --> 00:53:29.719
bit more representative of where we can reasonably expect team performance to be moving

00:53:29.719 --> 00:53:35.560
forward. So, you know, just think from like a weighting standpoint or just kind of the types

00:53:35.560 --> 00:53:42.439
of data that we emphasize in training our models. I'll say to some extent, we do try to directly

00:53:42.439 --> 00:53:47.479
incorporate some team performance dynamic elements into our models, whether that's a competitive

00:53:47.479 --> 00:53:53.719
lens or playoff probabilities. There's some somewhat easy things that we can calculate

00:53:54.600 --> 00:54:01.239
that we can sort of update over time, but it's a hard problem. Yep, definitely. Thank you.

00:54:01.879 --> 00:54:07.800
Thank you. I see Ronald asked a great question, and I think he had to drop to another meeting,

00:54:07.800 --> 00:54:13.159
so I'm just going to read it, but earlier when we were talking about presenting deliverables,

00:54:13.159 --> 00:54:18.760
you mentioned Markdown, or Markdown and Shiny. The question was, to what extent is leadership

00:54:18.760 --> 00:54:25.800
able to process this information, or do you guide leadership through the results along those lines?

00:54:26.280 --> 00:54:32.760
I think my best answer to that would be it's highly specific based on the individual characteristics

00:54:32.760 --> 00:54:38.919
of those individuals, and we sort of have the full gamut of, you know, my direct boss

00:54:39.639 --> 00:54:43.399
loves to get into the weeds. He wants to understand, why did you choose

00:54:43.399 --> 00:54:48.840
Markdown, or why did you choose Shiny, or why did you choose Markdown, or why did you choose

00:54:49.080 --> 00:54:55.719
of, you know, my direct boss loves to get into the weeds. He wants to understand, why did you choose

00:54:56.439 --> 00:55:01.639
this algorithm versus that. What happens if you change these assumptions, and so we spend a lot

00:55:01.639 --> 00:55:06.600
of time, you know, looking at in our script, and like, here's consensually what's going on,

00:55:06.600 --> 00:55:13.239
and like, here's the relative impact of these different assumptions. My boss sort of over

00:55:13.239 --> 00:55:18.439
indexes on that side of the things. On the other side, you've got other individuals who don't

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:23.239
not, they don't have the appetite, but they're more focused on the business outcome, and it's been

00:55:23.239 --> 00:55:27.000
somewhat of an iterative process to understand what resonates to what audience, and

00:55:28.439 --> 00:55:33.239
tailoring and catering those deliverables to those individuals.

00:55:36.439 --> 00:55:43.320
Thank you. Libby, I also think you had a question earlier around the biggest false

00:55:43.320 --> 00:55:48.120
assumptions that people generally make. Do you want to add any context to that one?

00:55:49.399 --> 00:55:53.959
I think that I've just been thinking a lot about assumptions lately, and how I'm usually wrong when

00:55:53.959 --> 00:56:01.879
I make assumptions about how other organizations, or even individuals use data, and the level of

00:56:01.879 --> 00:56:07.560
complexity that they actually use them at, and the application areas. So, sports is something I'm not

00:56:07.560 --> 00:56:12.199
familiar with, and I would like to kind of ask what the biggest assumption is that people make

00:56:13.159 --> 00:56:14.520
that's just totally wrong.

00:56:17.399 --> 00:56:22.919
Somewhat tongue-in-cheek, but the question I still feel from friends, family, people I meet is like,

00:56:22.919 --> 00:56:28.840
am I hanging out in the clubhouse, and like having dinner with with our players, and that's like

00:56:28.840 --> 00:56:37.879
could not be part of the truth. You know, all those guys, they're kind of doing their own thing,

00:56:38.600 --> 00:56:48.520
but I think sort of more directly to your point on sort of assumptions about our core business

00:56:48.520 --> 00:56:59.239
operations. I think people have a lot of assumptions about where decisions are made,

00:56:59.239 --> 00:57:07.000
and sort of who is running the show to some extent, and pretty much all of your major sports

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:11.639
teams are in some capacity owned by private ownership group, and those owners have different

00:57:11.639 --> 00:57:18.280
media personalities themselves, and individual and family brands, that depending on the organization,

00:57:18.280 --> 00:57:23.320
they may or may not have anything to do with the day-to-day operations, but nonetheless,

00:57:23.320 --> 00:57:30.520
when you, you know, if you follow Twitter, or sort of major media outlets, the characterization of

00:57:30.520 --> 00:57:37.399
the decision-making process as it gets described by the media is often pretty far from,

00:57:38.280 --> 00:57:44.439
you know, what I observe on a day-to-day basis, and by and large, it's one of those things that

00:57:44.439 --> 00:57:48.760
we're not really equipped, or wouldn't necessarily be in our best interest to

00:57:48.760 --> 00:57:53.560
try and change those perceptions, so we just kind of shrug your shoulders and go on,

00:57:53.959 --> 00:58:01.399
but it's interesting seeing how stuff that I am directly involved in behind the scenes

00:58:01.399 --> 00:58:05.320
ends up getting portrayed in the media, and sometimes it's spot on, and other times you're

00:58:05.320 --> 00:58:16.120
just kind of like, that's not how this works. Thank you, Chase. As we get to the top of the

00:58:16.120 --> 00:58:20.679
hour, I know some people might have to run, so I just want to ask what's the best way to

