get in touch with you if people have follow-up questions, or if they're interested in any of the

00:58:25.479 --> 00:58:31.399
roles? Is it LinkedIn? Yeah, I'd say I'm pretty easy to track down on LinkedIn, so I'd please

00:58:31.399 --> 00:58:37.320
encourage anyone to reach out via LinkedIn if you have any questions specific to the roles,

00:58:37.320 --> 00:58:40.919
certainly, but more generally, if you have an interest or just want to learn more about

00:58:41.800 --> 00:58:46.760
the sports industry. I obviously know the most about baseball, but have some decent perspective

00:58:47.080 --> 00:58:54.840
on other leagues as well, but yeah, please do reach out. I'm usually pretty good about responding.

00:58:57.159 --> 00:59:01.879
Awesome. Thank you, Chase. If it's okay, can I ask you maybe one or two more questions?

00:59:02.679 --> 00:59:10.280
I just want to make sure I didn't miss any. I'd love to hear what advice you have for

00:59:10.840 --> 00:59:14.919
maybe someone who's on the call right now that's hoping to get into a leadership position,

00:59:15.639 --> 00:59:20.360
and how they could move from being that individual contributor into leadership.

00:59:23.159 --> 00:59:30.280
I feel like the biggest jump there, it's probably not in the hard skills

00:59:31.239 --> 00:59:36.919
category, I think, in order to move up. I sort of think of the hard skill, you know, the proficiency

00:59:36.919 --> 00:59:41.800
and excellence in what I think of like the hard data science type skills, that's somewhat of a

00:59:41.800 --> 00:59:50.280
table stakes criteria. So you need to show a sort of minimum level of competency or

00:59:50.280 --> 00:59:54.760
excellence in that category, but where I think you can start to differentiate yourself

00:59:55.479 --> 01:00:01.800
is more in the soft skills. It's the leadership, it's the negotiation, it's the team building,

01:00:02.520 --> 01:00:11.479
it's sort of all the stuff that, you know, can be described as like the soft fluffy skills.

01:00:12.360 --> 01:00:17.800
But when you think about, I think, high performing organizations have tightly aligned

01:00:18.520 --> 01:00:24.520
strategy and data analytics functions. And so when I think about what does a aspiring leader

01:00:24.520 --> 01:00:30.280
need to do, it's starting to develop a knack for what is the strategy of the organization,

01:00:30.280 --> 01:00:35.399
and how can I influence that. Data, in a lot of ways, is a tool that can very meaningfully

01:00:35.399 --> 01:00:41.000
improve organizations. But it's sort of, I think you can really differentiate yourself on

01:00:42.120 --> 01:00:47.800
sort of outperforming your competitors, in some sense, and those soft skills.

01:00:51.320 --> 01:00:55.560
Thank you, Chase. And I just want to say, if I've missed anybody's questions,

01:00:55.560 --> 01:01:01.879
I'm trying to slide through in the chat here, but please feel free to just unmute yourself and jump

01:01:01.879 --> 01:01:12.280
in live too. Let's do a quick check. I don't see anyone that unmuted. One last question, Chase,

01:01:12.280 --> 01:01:18.360
I'd love to ask you. I'm trying to help bring more resources together for someone who's just

01:01:18.360 --> 01:01:23.719
trying to start advocating for data science internally, and maybe they're the first data

01:01:23.719 --> 01:01:33.399
person. How would you, I guess, tell someone to go about that process if they're in a position

01:01:33.399 --> 01:01:38.120
where they actually just have to start at getting approval to even use some of these tools?

01:01:39.320 --> 01:01:46.600
Yeah, I think where my head initially goes, and this sort of goes back to some of my MBA

01:01:47.239 --> 01:01:52.280
classes, but I think it's a pretty simple framework of what's the ROI that you think

01:01:52.280 --> 01:01:57.879
you could reasonably drive? And right, so I would think about it of engaging with

01:01:58.840 --> 01:02:03.000
each sort of the major stakeholders in an organization, and understanding what are

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:09.320
your problems, and basically what, how you can think about it in terms of revenue, or just like

01:02:09.320 --> 01:02:15.000
efficiency, right? If this business unit is operating at 80 percent efficiency, what's it

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:21.560
mean to the business if we could move that to 85 percent or 90 percent? Think about some way to

01:02:21.560 --> 01:02:29.000
quantify that, balance that up against whatever the sort of what resources you need to bring to

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:33.879
the table to unlock that five or ten percent improvement. And that, you know, I think about

01:02:33.879 --> 01:02:38.360
that in sort of the broadest sense of its tech count, its technology, its investment, data

01:02:38.360 --> 01:02:43.080
warehousing, right? Sort of depending on where that organization is, that could go in a lot of

01:02:43.080 --> 01:02:53.800
different ways, but, you know, where, you know, for my group, we think about driving essentially a

01:02:53.800 --> 01:02:58.360
5x return on the investments that the organization make in our group, and that's the sort of the

01:02:58.360 --> 01:03:06.840
benchmark and the threshold that I'm held accountable to. It's worked well here, and I

01:03:06.840 --> 01:03:12.600
think it's a good sort of forcing function to make sure you're focusing your time on the right

01:03:12.600 --> 01:03:15.080
problems that can sort of meaningfully drive the business forward.

01:03:17.479 --> 01:03:23.560
Definitely. Thank you so much, Chase. I really appreciate you joining and jumping on here and

